peans. The reception visitors received illustrate the dynamics of empire and international relations. Ceremonies, speeches and meetings formed part of the popular culture of empire and monarchy. Mixed in with pageantry and protocol were profound questions about the role of monarchs, imperial governance, relationships between metropolitan and overseas elites, and evolving expressions of nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2018. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAsia.  aBritish princes.  aBritish subjects.  aBritishness.  aColonialism.  aEmperor Khai Dinh.  aEmpire.  aImperial citizenship.  aKaiser Wilhelm II.  aKing Sisowath.  aMaharaja of Gondal.  aModern Europe.  aMonarchy.  aPrince Alfred Ernest Albert.  aPrinces.  aRoyal Navy.  aRoyal tours.  aRoyalty.  aSmuts's Raj.  aSultan Alauddin of Aceh.  aTravel.  aentourage.  aglobal tours.  aimperial authority.  aroyal personage.  aroyal visitor.1 aAldrich, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldrich, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFitzpatrick, Matthew P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeen, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCreery, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCreery, Cindy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aProtschky, Susie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReed, Charles V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSapire, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeymour, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTa